<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{kashira}}}} is a sentence ending particle mainly used by women and usually is translated as "I wonder".
</p>

<p>
The equivalent male particle is <a href="grammar-particle-kana.html">@HI{{kana}}</a>.
<p>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{kashira}}}} can indicate uncertainty.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KJ{{mechanism^contraption}}no@KJ{{use}}i@KJ{{direction}},go@KJ{{exist}}deirasshaimasu@EM{{kashira}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I wonder if you are aquainted with how this machine works?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{kashira}}}} can mark a question to oneself.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{mou@KJ{{homecoming}}ttemoiino@EM{{kashira}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I wonder if it's OK if I leave now?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{kashira}}}} can indicate a hope or a muted request.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{konpyu-ta-}}no@KJ{{use}}i@KJ{{direction}},@KJ{{teach}}eteitadakeru@EM{{kashira}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I wonder if you could teach me how to operate this computer?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{kashira}}}} comes from @HI{{kashiranai}} meaning "I don't know if", but now expresses the idea of "I wonder ...".
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{kashira}}}} cannot be used to express a past-tense situation. To do that, follow it with @HI{{to@KJ{{think}}tta}}.
</p>

